{{orphan|date=September 2010}}
'''Steinbier''' ({{IPA-de|ˈʃtaɪnˌbiːɐ|pron}}, [[German language|German]] for ''stone beer'') is a type of [[beer]] that was predominant in [[Carinthia (state)|Carinthia]] until the beginning of the 20th century. It was also commonin [[Scandinavia]], [[Franconia]] and south-western [[Germany]].<ref>http://www.schleppe.at/content/sl/unternehmen/chronik/index.html</ref>
Steinbier is not mashed in [[kettle]]s, but in wooden tubs. Its name is derived from the hot stones that were put into the mashing tubs to achieve the required temperature for production. Due to the contact of the glowing, hot stones&mdash;often heated directly in the fire&mdash;with the malt, the resulting beer has a taste of [[caramel]] and [[soot]]. This was a traditional brewing process; [[top-fermenting]] [[yeast]]s and a fruity taste of [[ester]] were usual and there was no emphasis on long term storability. Steinbier was usually not filtered.<ref>http://www.brauen.de/braulexikon/biermarken-sorten/steinbier/</ref> {{commonscat}}
