{{unreferenced|date=August 2011}}
'''High gravity beer''' refers to specialty [[beer]] either [[Microbrewery#Craft beer|craft beers]] or [[malt liquor]]s with an increased specific [[Gravity (alcoholic beverage)|gravity]]. A beer with an original gravity 1.070 is generally considered to be high. High gravity beers are a traditional expression of beer making in [[Europe]], but only a small percentage of [[Microbrewery|microbreweries]] in the [[United States]] produce them. They may be more expensive than [[Mass production|mass-produced]] beer due to larger amounts of high quality grains or malt used, or in the case of malt liquor lower in cost or equal to other mass-produced beers, and full of more filler grains or [[adjuncts]]. They may be more flavorful, intended to be sipped and savored, and are often [[Wine and food matching|paired]] with carefully prepared foods, or in the case of high gravity malt liquor, they may sacrifice some flavor for an inexpensive boost of alcohol level, and may be paired with [[junk food]].

==Alcohol content==
High gravity beer tends to have higher [[Alcohol by volume|alcohol content]] compared to other beers due to the concentration of [[sugar]] and flavor-enhancing ingredients at the beginning of the brewing process. Steel Reserve, one example of a high gravity lager beer contains 8.1% alcohol.

